definition.value: A member of the juvenile hormone family of compounds that is the methyl ester of  (2E,6E,10R,11S)-10,11-epoxy-3,7,11-trimethyltrideca-2,6-dienoic acid.
A ceramide in which the acyl group and the sphingoid base contain a total of 36 carbon atoms and 2 double bonds.
Any saturated fatty acid containing 24 carbons and 0 double bonds.
The (2R,3S)-diastereomer of 2,3-dimethylmalic acid.

A biphenyl that is 1,1'-biphenyl substituted by a methyl group at position 3, a (2-{6-[4-carboxy-5-(trifluoromethyl)-1H-pyrazol-1-yl]pyridin-2-yl}phenoxy)methyl group at position 4 and by a trifluoromethoxy at position 4'. It is a potent guanylate cyclase activator.
A trace radioisotope of argon with atomic mass of 38.964313 and a half-life of 269 years.
The (R)-enantiomer of 2-ethylmalic acid.
A 2-fluorophenylalanine that has L-configuration.
A 2-fluorophenylalanine that has D-configuration.
A phenylalanine derivative in which the hydrogen at position 2 on the benzene ring is replaced by a fluoro group.

A peptide zwitterion obtained from the tranfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group of any tripeptide. It contains an equal number of positively-charged and negatively-charged functional groups. Major structure at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino terminus of glycylsarcosine. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
Any  deoxyaltrose in which the hydroxy group at position 6 has been replaced by a hydrogen.
A 2-hydroxydicarboxylic acid that is malic acid (hydroxysuccinic acid) in which the hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a methyl group.
A dexoyhexose that is any altrose having at least one hydroxy group replaced by hydrogen.
A member of the class of pinoresinols that is (+)-pinoresinol carrying a hydroxy group at position 1S.
A cholestanoid that is cholest-4-en-3-one which carries a hydroxy group at position 25.
A linear amino tetrasaccharide comprised of alpha-L-fucosyl, beta-D-galactosyl, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl and N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine residues linked sequentially (1->2), (1->4) and (1->3).
A peptide zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino terminus of Leu-Pro.
A peptide zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino terminus of Ala-Pro.
A tripeptide zwitterion resulting from the transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group of Ala-Pro-Gly. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A tripeptide zwitterion resulting from the transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group of Gly-Gly-Ile. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
